					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sal=
t content in the soil</div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Salinity.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.=
wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Salinity.jpg/250px-Salinity.jpg"=
 decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"169" class=3D"mw-file-element" =
data-file-width=3D"663" data-file-height=3D"447"></a><figcaption>Visibly sa=
lt-affected soils on rangeland in Colorado. Salts dissolved from the soil a=
ccumulate at the soil surface and are deposited on the ground and at the ba=
se of the fence post.</figcaption></figure>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Incrusta%C3%A7%C3%A3o_salina_1-PET_Solos_UESC.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
9/97/Incrusta%C3%A7%C3%A3o_salina_1-PET_Solos_UESC.jpg/250px-Incrusta%C3%A7=
%C3%A3o_salina_1-PET_Solos_UESC.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"249" heigh=
t=3D"187" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4160" data-file-heig=
ht=3D"3120"></a><figcaption>Saline incrustation in a PVC irrigation pipe fr=
om Brazil</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Soil salinity</b> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sal=
t_(chemistry)" title=3D"Salt (chemistry)">salt</a> content in the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil" title=3D"Soil">soil</a>; the proces=
s of increasing the salt content is known as <b>salinization</b> (also call=
ed <b>salination</b> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_a=
nd_British_English_spelling_differences" title=3D"American and British Engl=
ish spelling differences">American English</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite=
_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Salts occur naturally within soils and water. Salinizat=
ion can be caused by natural processes such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Mineral_weathering" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mineral wea=
thering">mineral weathering</a> or by the gradual withdrawal of an ocean. I=
t can also come about through artificial processes such as <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrigation" title=3D"Irrigation">irrigation</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Road_salt" title=3D"Road salt">r=
oad salt</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Natural_occurrence">Natural=
 occurrence</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Soil_salinity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Nat=
ural occurrence"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_(chemistry)" title=3D"Salt=
 (chemistry)">Salts</a> are a natural component in soils and water.
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion" title=3D"Ion">ions</a> re=
sponsible for salinization are: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/So=
dium" title=3D"Sodium">Na<sup>+</sup></a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Potassium" title=3D"Potassium">K<sup>+</sup></a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calcium" title=3D"Calcium">Ca<sup>2+</sup></a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnesium" title=3D"Magnesium">Mg<su=
p>2+</sup></a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chlorine" title=
=3D"Chlorine">Cl<sup>=E2=88=92</sup></a>.<br>
</p><p>Over long periods of time, as soil minerals <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Weathering" title=3D"Weathering">weather</a> and release s=
alts, these salts are flushed or leached out of the soil by drainage water =
in areas with sufficient precipitation. In addition to mineral weathering, =
salts are also deposited via dust and precipitation.  Salts may accumulate =
in dry regions, leading to naturally saline soils. This is the case, for ex=
ample, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salinity_in_Australia" t=
itle=3D"Salinity in Australia">large parts of Australia</a>.=20
</p><p>Human practices can increase the salinity of soils by the addition o=
f salts in irrigation water. Proper irrigation management can prevent salt =
accumulation by providing adequate drainage water to leach added salts from=
 the soil. Disrupting drainage patterns that provide leaching can also resu=
lt in salt accumulations. An example of this occurred in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egypt" title=3D"Egypt">Egypt</a> in 1970 when the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aswan_Dam" title=3D"Aswan Dam">Aswan=
 High Dam</a> was built. The change in the level of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Ground_water" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ground water=
">ground water</a> before the construction had enabled <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_erosion" title=3D"Soil erosion">soil erosion</a>,=
 which led to high concentration of salts in the water table. After the con=
struction, the continuous high level of the water table led to the saliniza=
tion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arable_land" title=3D"Arab=
le land">arable land</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fac=
t" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span tit=
le=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (June 2020)">citatio=
n needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Sodic_soils">Sodic soils</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSoil_salinity&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Sodic soils"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>When the Na<sup>+</sup> (sodium) predominates, soils can become <b>sodic=
</b>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PH" title=3D"PH">pH</a> =
of sodic soils may be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acidic_soil"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Acidic soil">acidic</a>, neutral, or <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alkaline_soil" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Alkaline soil">alkaline</a>.=20
</p><p>Sodic soils present particular challenges because they tend to have =
very poor structure which limits or prevents <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Water_infiltration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Water infiltr=
ation">water infiltration</a> and drainage. They tend to accumulate certain=
 elements like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boron" title=3D"Bor=
on">boron</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molybdenum" titl=
e=3D"Molybdenum">molybdenum</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Rhizosphere" title=3D"Rhizosphere">root zone</a> at levels that may be=
 toxic for plants.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The most c=
ommon compound used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_recla=
mation" title=3D"Land reclamation">reclamation</a> of sodic soil is <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gypsum" title=3D"Gypsum">gypsum</a>, and =
some plants that are tolerant to salt and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/w/index.php?title=3DIon_toxicity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" clas=
s=3D"new" title=3D"Ion toxicity (page does not exist)">ion toxicity</a> may=
 present strategies for improvement.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-3"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;"=
>[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" titl=
e=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title=3D"The material near this tag fai=
led verification of its source citation(s). (July 2023)">failed verificatio=
n</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The term "sodic soil" is sometimes used imprecisely in scholarship. =
It's been used interchangeably with the term <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Alkali_soil" title=3D"Alkali soil">alkali soil</a>, which is use=
d in two meanings: 1) a soil with a pH greater than 8.2, 2) soil with an ex=
changeable sodium content above 15% of exchange capacity. The term "alkali =
soil" is often, but not always, used for soils that meet both of these char=
acteristics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Dry_land_salinity">Dry land=
 salinity</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSo=
il_salinity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Dry l=
and salinity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dryland_salinity" title=3D"Dryl=
and salinity">Salinity in drylands</a> can occur when the water table is be=
tween two and three metres from the surface of the soil.  The salts from th=
e groundwater are raised by capillary action to the surface of the soil. Th=
is occurs when groundwater is saline (which is true in many areas), and is =
favored by land use practices allowing more rainwater to enter the aquifer =
than it could accommodate. For example, the clearing of trees for agricultu=
re is a major reason for dryland salinity in some areas, since deep rooting=
 of trees has been replaced by shallow rooting of annual crops.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Salinity_due_to_irrigation"=
>Salinity due to irrigation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DSoil_salinity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"=
Edit section: Salinity due to irrigation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Salinity_from_irrigation.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D=
"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Salinity_from_ir=
rigation.png/500px-Salinity_from_irrigation.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"400" height=3D"126" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"878" d=
ata-file-height=3D"276"></a><figcaption>Rain or irrigation, in the absence =
of leaching, can bring salts to the surface by capillary action.</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_impacts_of_irrigat=
ion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Environmental impacts of irrigation">En=
vironmental impacts of irrigation</a></div>
<p>Salinity from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrigation" title=
=3D"Irrigation">irrigation</a> can occur over time wherever irrigation occu=
rs, since almost all water (even natural rainfall) contains some dissolved =
salts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When the plants use th=
e water, the salts are left behind in the soil and eventually begin to accu=
mulate. This water in excess of plant needs is called the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaching_model" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Leac=
hing model">leaching fraction</a>. Salinization from irrigation water is al=
so greatly increased by poor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drain=
age" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Drainage">drainage</a> and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biosalinity" title=3D"Biosalinity">use of sali=
ne water</a> for irrigating agricultural crops.
</p><p>Salinity in urban areas often results from the combination of irriga=
tion and groundwater processes. Irrigation is also now common in cities (ga=
rdens and recreation areas).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Consequences_of_soil_salini=
ty">Consequences of soil salinity</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DSoil_salinity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Consequences of soil salinity"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The consequences of salinity are
</p>
<ul><li>Detrimental effects on plant growth and yield</li>
<li>Damage to infrastructure (roads, bricks, corrosion of pipes and cables)=
</li>
<li>Reduction of water quality for users, sedimentation problems, increased=
 leaching of metals,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> especial=
ly copper, cadmium, manganese and zinc.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_erosion" title=3D"Soil er=
osion">Soil erosion</a> ultimately, when crops are too strongly affected by=
 the amounts of salts.</li>
<li>More energy required to desalinate</li></ul>
<p>Salinity is an important <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_d=
egradation" title=3D"Land degradation">land degradation</a> problem. Soil s=
alinity can be reduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaching=
_(agriculture)" title=3D"Leaching (agriculture)">leaching</a> soluble salts=
 out of soil with excess irrigation water.  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Soil_salinity_control" title=3D"Soil salinity control">Soil salin=
ity control</a> involves <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Watertabl=
e_control" title=3D"Watertable control">watertable control</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaching_model" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Leaching model">flushing</a> in combination with <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tile_drainage" title=3D"Tile drainage">tile drainage</=
a> or another form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drainage_sys=
tem_(agriculture)" title=3D"Drainage system (agriculture)">subsurface drain=
age</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-W=
aterlog_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
oil_salinity#cite_note-Waterlog-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A comprehensive treatment of =
soil salinity is available from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/United_Nations" title=3D"United Nations">United Nations</a> <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Food_and_Agriculture_Organization" title=3D"Foo=
d and Agriculture Organization">Food and Agriculture Organization</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Salt_tolerance_of_crops">Sa=
lt tolerance of crops</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DSoil_salinity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Salt tolerance of crops"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_tolerance_of_cr=
ops" title=3D"Salt tolerance of crops">Salt tolerance of crops</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maas%E2%80%93=
Hoffman_model" title=3D"Maas=E2=80=93Hoffman model">Maas=E2=80=93Hoffman mo=
del</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Van_Genuchten%E2%80%93=
Gupta_model" title=3D"Van Genuchten=E2=80=93Gupta model">Van Genuchten=E2=
=80=93Gupta model</a></div>
<p>High levels of soil salinity can be tolerated if salt-tolerant plants ar=
e grown.  Sensitive crops lose their vigor already in slightly saline soils=
, most crops are negatively affected by (moderately) saline soils, and only=
 salinity-resistant crops thrive in severely saline soils. The University o=
f Wyoming<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Alan_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-Alan-10"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and =
the Government of Alberta<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Albert_11-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-Albert-=
11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> report data on the salt tolerance of plants.
</p><p>Field data in irrigated lands, under farmers' conditions, are scarce=
, especially in developing countries. However, some on-farm surveys have be=
en made in Egypt,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> India,<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and Pakistan.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil=
_salinity#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some examples are shown in the followi=
ng gallery, with crops arranged from sensitive to very tolerant.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
oil_salinity#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil_salinity#cite_note-16"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
